Parliament does not support the amendment that frees Tymoshenko
Today, the Ukrainian Parliament, while amending the Criminal Procedure Code, rejected the attempt to repeal the article condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment, which would have led to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the economic offence relief bill.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was deemed unprofitable.
The verdict is not final; the court will hear Tymoshenko's appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, which condemned the former prime minister, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would take 226 votes to ratify.
