Nutrition for children with obesity: No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% are obese.
According to a recent study, children with obesity are usually born into families with unhealthy lifestyles.
We see again the importance of the environment and the patterns of behavior that accompany a person for their healthy development.
For example, sausages are almost twice as common on the tables of children with obesity as in families with normal weight.
More than 19 percent of obese children ate potatoes for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity.
Moreover, families of children with obesity do not engage in sports, but this is true of most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children said their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted on 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last school year; it involved nearly 900 elementary school students throughout Bohemia.
The event Obesity is no accident, it was held for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišťovna and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12 thousand students of 4th-8th grade have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate exercise are key determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who are either overweight or obese.
"For example, only half of those surveyed said they ate five meals a day, breakfast, lunch, and dinner, which is a must", says one study.
No lunch and no sausage in the evenings .
Experts warn that even relative details such as regular family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of schoolchildren's families have breakfast together.
Most families have breakfast separately.
The worst finding was that one in ten families didn't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
Research has shown that fried foods are more common in families with children who are obese.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet cooling drinks every day (70%).
While more than 40 percent of children are regularly involved in sports, that number is more than doubled - to 15 percent - when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to make their own menu based on the products offered and their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of 12-15 year-olds in the Czech Republic are far from ideal when it comes to healthy eating".
Their favorite food includes a large amount of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
"The popularity of soft drinks is particularly alarming", says the final part of the study.
As the main meal, pasta beat the bird with a small weight.
However, the children were barely interested in bean, fish, and vegetable dishes.
The Pursuit of a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also found that children are willing to change their eating habits provided they are given the right information.
"Many study controls showed a significant shift in preference for healthy eating when they completed the questionnaire after the lecture", the project concludes.
This was especially evident, for example, in the case of sweet, cool drinks - more children were starting to prefer them to just water.
In addition, children were more likely to eat poultry and fish as a main course, limiting the number of sweet dishes and pastries.
