V for Speed: Running takes place in America.
The review
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambitions were met to some extent, but that didn't matter, because nobody wanted to do the overwork.
Before the release of the new version with the subtitle "Fleeing" there were high hopes.
It was expected to move the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demo versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, the result is very different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade game, but the overall impression is ruined by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, in reality, it's not a mistake, but an expression of the inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts off very well.
You become part of a story where the protagonist, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by taking part in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the West Coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to be the first to get to New York.
There are some interesting features to this idea.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes its own route, with individual stages taking place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So there's no feeling that the game is always the same.
Although the graphics are on the same level as the previous installments in the series, some tracks are enjoyable to watch.
And yet the game doesn't cause any strong emotions.
Although it is a pleasure to drive through the desert, through the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains.
Besides, the race comes alive with an unusual detail every now and then.
For example, in the desert, you're hit by a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in the avalanche.
The individual races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
Some time you try to outrun several competitors (a normal race essentially); then you try to improve the time (a standard race with a second meter); or you compete against one opponent.
Besides, you sometimes run into the police, which makes your job even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where Jack runs away from someone most of the time and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not that complicated.
Although surprisingly, these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (just three to be exact).
It turns out that it's actually good for the game because it's not boring; considering all of the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The racing model follows in the footsteps of previous models.
It means that it's no longer special, but it's not a disadvantage.
If you're looking for a real-life simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
And yet this model of driving is very suitable for dynamic racing, although there are better options available on the market.
It's all right.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't that good.
You don't expect any complicated transformations and collisions from this game, but if you don't have a clue before you hit an object, how your car will behave, something's wrong.
Usually, when you're driving or passing cars in a tight flow, you sometimes touch another car slightly, and yet sometimes in a similar situation, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or the beads were broken.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are designed so that if you crash or get off the track, the game will take you back to the point where it broke.
Still, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use all of them, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work, but you can't rely on it completely.
Sometimes restarting is not enough, and you have to memorize a particular race track.
The important disadvantage of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you'll encounter civilian cars in a certain place in the same configuration whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially irritating when you see your opponent easily moving between two cars moving in opposite directions, whereas when you're there, the cars are already positioned so you either need to go around them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's all set up so that the situation is always right in front of you.
There are other advantages to competitors.
During the game, you discover several places where, regardless of the time, the same opponent is chasing you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand up to you no matter what.
The thing is, when he drives in front of you, he makes your vision worse, which leads to one or more accidents on that stretch.
You can understand trying to make the game more interesting and adrenaline-filled, but it's so obvious it's quickly becoming irritating.
It's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the game is so entertaining and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what doesn't make you miss -- a concept with 50 unique tracks, a racing sequence or something.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to keep track of the gas stations along the way, because that's where your car can change, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars for straight roads; and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, such as on curved mountain tracks.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; it's individual racing that you learn throughout the game.
Here you win medals for your personal business and points for the challenges and story modes.
There are many ways to get a higher level of driving: from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the Autolog online feature, which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players and provides communication with the public.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race in a row.
You and your car get into a subway tunnel (we'll assume that) where you're running on the tracks in the dark (we'll assume that).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (we'll assume that) when suddenly a subway train comes up behind you, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For days, our editorial team debated whether the game was actually created without anyone thinking for a second, or whether the creators really thought we were such idiots.
The technical aspect of the game is not that special; but the overall impression of the video game is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
It's a shame that at some critical moments, the quality of the recording, sometimes quite strongly, declines.
This is especially true in high-stakes incidents where a good recording would not help you much either.
The sound is fine; the soundtrack is for the amateur.
To appeal to a wider audience of young people, the soundtrack included "compositions of different styles"; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: Running is pretty messy.
If the game avoided obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Running is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of incompleteness.
Of course, it's a good time, but be prepared for the shortcomings that will blind you like an airport spotlight.
The chorus of Karlov University will perform at the concert "Students in barkhat"
For the third year in a row, the Festa Academia festival is offering to combine International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical event.
He'll be presenting about 20 choirs from schools and universities.
The main event of the festival is two concerts, which will take place on November 17.
"Karlov University is taking an active part in the festival".
"The choir members include the Choir of the Faculty of Education and Humanities; Václav Gambl, the rector, will join the committee", said Jacob Chalon, head of the organizing committee.
The culmination will be a free public concert of school choirs, which will take place at 2 p.m. on November 17 at the National Technical Library in Davice.
The work "Jazz Mass", composed by the famous Czech jazzman, Karel Ružicki, is also included in the program.
In the evening, the official National House in Winogrady will hold a concert "Students in Barchate", with the participation of choruses of universities, including the chorus of the University of Karlovy Vary.
The purpose of Festa Academica is to celebrate the International Student Day and to honour the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution; as well as to present the public with the highest quality choral music and to develop creative interaction among young people.
The main organizer is the Českých pěveckých sborů (Czech choirs) in cooperation with the Johann Kepler High School.
The event is being held with the support of Bogusław Svoboda, Lord Mayor of Prague, and Watsław Gamp, Rector of Karlov University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The program offers both official concerts and numerous musical meetings, student happy-goes, daytime performances, etc.
For more information please visit the festival website: www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unwelcome and sceptical of the euro.
"The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable disagreement between the various organizations".
"I didn't expect such a brutal war".
"It takes five or six years before the situation at least stabilizes, calms down and all the players get used to their new roles", EU ambassador Milena Vitsenova began her lecture at the law school.
She demonstrated how much she adhered to her motto "Clear and Open Europe" in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simply and understandably that many of the lecturers at UC Law would be envious.
Moreover, Vitsenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was just a gray office mouse who couldn't play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he did his part".
"He is a man who can listen to 27 Member States at once, communicate with them well and has a clear idea of the direction in which the EU should be developed".
She explained her new position as the EU's representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number should I call?" that is, as an important step towards unifying and increasing transparency of EU policies towards countries like China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vitsenova further focused on a key EU programme in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech presidency a success last year.
The Czechs were dealing with an impending financial crisis; they overcame this crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Currently, the Czech representatives in the EU are very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the ongoing fallout.
It is also necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is not easy given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be given preference; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these issues are in the upcoming programme.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans she had brought to Brussels: "On Europe, in a clear language".
"I really don't like abbreviations, foreign words, and jargon that nobody understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese.'
It also intends to use the EU environment more effectively and to attract more Czechs to European organisations.
High-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered euroskeptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive side of things.
She wants more Czech representatives involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters, with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful presidency of the Czech Republic, she noted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary and we have a Slovak, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the matter, the Visegrad group again?' and he's not happy about it.
In the future, the Union is expected to have new, strict rules for the budgetary policies of the participating states.
Compared to the new European Federation, it considers the idea of a two-speed, if not a multi-speed Europe, more realistic.
"We have countries both inside and outside the eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area, and we already have the Cooperation Institute".
"It was said for the first time that countries that wanted to unite should unite, while those that did not want to could stay out".
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe", Vitsenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all issues affecting the whole EU should be discussed by all participating countries, not just those in the Eurozone.
The history of the brand:
IBM's innovator is entering its second century.
If anyone wants to find the word that best expresses IMB strategy, the closest one is probably "long term".
IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution for the general public; the company is considered very modern, even though it was founded over a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was established by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He believed in his motto that many world problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the future giant's life unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson built up carefully.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a steady move into the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, even though it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, it has transformed technology, business and the company.
In the next hundred years, we hope to achieve even more", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO, on the anniversary.
A complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care as Batya did in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms, and a complex bonus system for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
IBM's long-term consumer relationship is equally advanced.
From the very beginning, the company was a brilliant application to talented people, and it was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, which gave it a great choice.
It's consistent with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan that a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmisano next year.
She worked at IBM for thirty years; she is currently the Director of Sales, Marketing and Development.
Over the last few years, IBM has been organizing meetings, online brainstorming, where many future innovations are born.
No wonder there's so many ideas -- there's about half a million people in the company.
A good name organization
The company's strong position in business is ensured by a strong internal and external image.
"From the very beginning, IBM was more of an organization than a technology company", Harvard Business School professor and IBM author Rosabette Moss Kanter told Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, it's a company that helps businesses solve business problems with technology", adds Forrester Research consultant Joe Colony.
As the company itself says, there's a difference between going into the market and creating it.
Over the course of a hundred years, IBM, or the "Blue Giant", as it is called in the United States because of its logo, has become one of the largest companies in the world.
It seems to be the most versatile technology company -- hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting -- from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include, for example, an ATM, a bank card, a financial swap, barcode, and a floppy disk.
With $220 billion, according to market capitalization, IBM this year became the second-largest technology company (first place behind Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all of its products were in the best interests of customers and fit the era.
"If your business is driven by moving forward, you can't be emotionally attached to the past", says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM is easy to lay the foundation for multiple platforms -- if they don't work, it abandons them.
It's different from its competitor Microsoft, which is based on and experiencing a downturn in Windows, its operating system.
Prospective technology
IBM's primary revenue comes from services, with about a fifth coming from computer programs and hardware.
In 1990, with a capital of twice that, it was the strongest equipment company.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-income assets, while investing $58 billion in promising technology.
It continued to invest even after 2008, when the current economic crisis hit the world for the first time.
IBM follows the example of its first CEO, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, it seems IBM hasn't done any damage to the current crisis.
Since the beginning of 2008, IBM's stock price has risen by a record 120 percent; the company's net earnings have been steadily increasing.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything except its own values.
So we can expect that even if another crisis breaks out, this flexible giant will handle the situation.
IBM history: from the cheese knife to spaceflight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago. Its original name was "Computing, Tabling, Record Corporation" which was quite complicated.
It was renamed IBM in 1924, and was originally used as a brand name for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundation for IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1880s.
They had technology like the legendary "table clock", which records the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also headed the company's board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired the CEO of his competitor, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the CEO threw the IBM founder out of the picture - Watson's ideas remain the foundation of an unbreakable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, started with the production and sale of various equipment for business - from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash machines.
In the first four years of Watson's tenure, revenues doubled to nine million dollars, and the company began a massive expansion to all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his son, Thomas Watson, Jr., took his place as director.
Under his leadership, IBM began developing artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control spaceflights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC that defined computer standards of the time, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the computer manufacturing business to Lenovo, a Chinese company, and bought the consulting business PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus focusing entirely on high-value-added services and consulting.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is to make smart use of technology in areas where it hasn't been planned yet, and improve road conditions and urban governance.
In the business world, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps business people control the entire business cycle.
IBM's traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM established its branch in 1932.
Today IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters of Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where a world-class research group on speech recognition also operates.
