The dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourism agencies could operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, tourist agencies of the time mostly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, for the holidays, Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balatón).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on Czech tourists' travel to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually through socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel on his own, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was required; otherwise, individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered travel to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" at the agency.
And that's not all.
A currency permit was required to travel to the West, and it was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, a practice that continues to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989, holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The big paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989, we couldn't freely visit the most popular country in Croatia today, because it was part of former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the need for visas to visit neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, and a huge wave of short trips began, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechs could not get enough of traveling west.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tents in parks because their income at the time was insufficient to afford a hotel or boarding house.
The typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring in their own food (consequences, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which, decades later, allows tourists to buy Western currency freely.
Our living standards and average income were rising, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines, and now, compared to the past, flights have become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed countries except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter, flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Today, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, happened in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, and our country has become one of the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history, in 2008, Czechs spent more than half their vacation abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their vacation abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
