Here's the tip: carefully cut this page and use it as a keyword.
You'll get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of people will be your GPS, your beacon in the moments when, like one of these men and women, you'll stray off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as "anti-history work".
It has few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; it has almost no ambassadors, skilled journalists, or discussions of tactics and combat technology.
It is not so much a book about what was, he explains, as a "book about what it was like". It is a "book about feelings, impressions, experiences, and states of mind".
The book "Beauty and Sorrow" has interwoven the experiences of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women over the years, on both sides of the front line, from school girls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and staff.
Some of these people will be heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses an arm or a leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are shining like church candles here, new ones being added to many others, and some of them going out.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
It's an amendment to the idea that World War I was just a tough trench war on the Western Front.
Beauty and Sorrow is a masterpiece of the other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are being hit by beehives; one of them is celebrating Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the cece flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like smokeless powder.
When a gunshot is heard nearby and you're a woman and you're home with your kids, will you stay or run?
Who's that anyway?
Almost no one understands what's going on and why we have to fight this war.
"The lack of facts", notes Mr. Englund, "is filled with speculation, speculation, hope, fear, compulsive ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors".
Beauty and Sorrow follows the fortunes of people like Florence Farmboro, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from memoirs, letters, and other published material.
The stories of their lives may be scary or exciting, but they are highly alive thanks to the minute details and details Mr. Englund collected.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to deal with it.
He tells the story of a German school girl, and he says, "Erzats, erzats everywhere".
"Coffee, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons".
He keeps talking about the German ersatz food.
He describes "meat of pressed rice, cooked in barley fat (and decorated with fake bone, made of wood); tobacco, made of dried roots and dried potato skin; shoes, cut with wood".
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes authorized for sausage production, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories tell of honor and courage.
One American observes the urge to be cruel and says of war: "You feel that, after all, that's what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, an evening paper or a bestseller and claim that this show is civilization and that under your rusty-fried shirt with a pair of scarves there is no barbarian".
A British soldier, on the other hand, realizes that he will most likely die and no one will notice or be saddened.
"When a person accepts the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think that it will be in front of an audience", he writes.
But it's the opposite, it's a lot like "a convicted man hanged in secret".
Other comments concern the old Europe, which is falling apart, and new forms of fear.
"The conflict was becoming more and more an economic competition", Mr. Englund writes, "a war of factories".
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the beast of the new century: a beautifully expressive and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-stitched costume who arranges a massacre while sitting at a desk".
People act in unpredictable ways: humble acts as much as heroism.
Mr. Englund told of soldiers who tried to get prostitutes to have a venereal disease to avoid service on the front lines.
"The most grotesque expression of this is the trade in honorary dung, which soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in hopes of getting into a hospital", he writes.
"All the desperate people rubbed his eyes, often leading to lifelong blindness".
Mr. Englund's prose translated from Swedish by Peter Graves is flexible but unpretentious, perfectly suited to his humanitarian task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how war "liberated forces beyond control: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People are starting to ask why their leaders force them to fight.
