Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just a regular guy who put his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to committing a mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared for his first open court hearing.
Although Breivik could operate alone, he was far from alone on the web: he spent a lot of time preparing for an attack behind his computer, talking to millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to approach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report on European cyberpopulism by the British research centre DEMOS.
The personal data on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint the demographic with scientific accuracy - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then put them on the market, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitude to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving their offices.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so surprising: Online right-wing supporters are mostly young men who are unhappy with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with their offline activity are smarter, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor".
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to explore everything in the world - from health issues to social trends expressed in "Likes", wall posts, and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook's "super-current" information is driving a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site's title in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows people to study people who can't be reached on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them".
"You would have to join a party, and they would never accept you", says Bartlett.
"Facebook excludes all this - you go directly to them".
Others say that this site could help identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that peers of students, such as their hostel instructors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who is too often updating his status as a drunk.
"You can't solve a problem without identifying it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute of Seattle.
"We found a way to identify children from the risk group who would otherwise not be detected".
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The site's data processing team has processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, midterm voter turnout in 2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mostly using information that only they have access to - cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the ability to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what happens when Facebook users become participants in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for doing offline research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the possibility of a researcher watching their profiles", says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using publicly accessible student Facebook pages.
"As far as they could imagine, it was just between them and their friends".
Then the question arises about the methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject of the study is extremely honest.
You can't tell on Facebook how much information on a user's profile or page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", says Selvin.
That's why, despite years of research in technology, Selvin thinks that a notebook and a pen are still the best research tools you can use.
"Nothing can replace going out into the real world and interacting with real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social, and most of social research is still happening offline".
