Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview that's showing at the theater this week.
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest discovery in a recently discovered interview, which they recalled in the lead-up to the opening screening in the major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and in manufacturing technology.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a thorough organizer and a moderniser of the manufacturing process, who believed that many business executives suffered from the "disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea from a great product separates a huge amount of skilled labor".
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the TV series Triumph of Nerves about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs on a unique, lengthy conversation.
By then, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was fired from Apple, and he was already working at his new computer company NeXT waiting for the massive Internet boom.
While a small portion of the interview was used in the Nerds, he says the original interviews were lost during transportation.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is coming out at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
To a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to present his technological philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
There are four different moments in an interview where there are large intervals between questions and answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems annoyed by the issues of the Kringley, causing him to move faster to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar, iPod and iPhone Lost Interview, there's something more horrifyingly prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about the post-mortem evaluations of Jobs, but there's something hurtful and inspiring about the job we see here, a troubled dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said it all here, he went and did it.
A little summary of seven important conclusions from the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All my time in business, I've been asking, 'Why do you do this?' and the answers you're always getting are, 'Oh, that's just the way it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks deeply about business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues to describe in detail his efforts to streamline Apple's reporting.
Disillusioned with the way he recorded expenses, which often started with "standard expenses" that were taken from the ceiling and then tracked down by "clearing", he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
The joke about the Pope:
Jobs details the blue box he made with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to hack into a phone company efficiently and make long-distance calls for free.
There's been a lot of talk about the device before, but the euphoria of Jobs here describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a cell phone, ordering a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
"We've covered the globe half a dozen times, and you've been screaming at the phone, and it's been going to the next phone a minute later", says Jobs, smiling.
"We were young, and all we learned was that we could master something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both knew a little bit, but we could make a little thing that could control a big thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have made it without it.
Jobs goes on to describe one famous escape he and Wozniak practically made by calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to call him on the phone, trying hard to copy Henry Kissinger.
