How to Catch a Liar
A quick look at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Kane is busy challenging accusations of sexual harassment by several women; each side is accusing the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania administration was charged with perjury for allegedly hiding that a retired football coach raped boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught talking to US President Barack Obama on a microphone that the Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies ruin careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Wayner made a fool of himself by denying his conclusions, which were quickly refuted by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with campaign finance fraud related to the cover-up of extramarital affairs.
And again, no one living at that time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton, who was lied to about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating in school and college exams are commonplace.
There were instances when teachers gave students answers to tests in order to get a good score for their own activities.
Teachers who are supposed to teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Research shows that you can be lied to 10 to 200 times in a day.
It's now assumed that a significant part of this is salvation lies.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of dating.
Detecting a lie or proving a lie is a skill that is necessary for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game, like, say, a charade where you have to say, "It's over!" detecting lies is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One study found that most of the old myths about lying had been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always get stuck, itchy, red or creamy.
It is not necessary to conclude that liars are difficult to spot and hard to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of the claims, the look, the structure of the questions, and the timing characteristics.
I've spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lying, and it's clear that lying detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and that helps you navigate in our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel free, controlling their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more often about others, usually to protect someone's feelings, that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are often false).
We also know that if you are perceived as a fraud, others will feel less guilty about cheating on you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
It's called "determining the initial state".
This helps provide a starting point for further evaluation of changes.
Watch your posture, laughter, voice characteristics.
You'd better know if a person is always knocking with his legs in a normal state, so you don't make unfair accusations when you see a knock in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups like red flags, not evidence of deception.
Cheaters can capture the upper part of their body when they're trying to remember their story, they can set their feet in the direction of the door, they can lean toward the exit, they can change their posture in a certain way, or they can show "relieving after an interview" -- that exaggerated breath of relief and a change of posture when all the complicated questions are behind them.
Investigators often falsify the end of questioning signal to just watch the relief after the interview.
So, listen to the speech of your subject.
Scott Peterson is known to have backed down and used his past to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which led to a nationwide manhunt.
The people who are in the mood can also use the distance in the speech, "I didn't have sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the complex question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely tangible.
Someone might use "qualification language" when answering a difficult question, "Well... to be honest... as far as I know... as far as I know".
This makes the response more emotional than actual, and it's often a red flag.
There is no magic to detect lies, but you can master the ability to detect deceit.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not falling prey to skilled cheaters in their professional and personal lives.
