The immigration is suspended
Lopez Cervantes said there's a demographic factor in the unemployment rate.
"The number of people who leave the state to seek work abroad in the United States has been limited, firstly because of the difficulty of entry, and secondly because once they enter, they already face many difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, resulting in rising unemployment", he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa's labor market analysis is getting worse when you look at the high number of labor violations that prevail, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the state's active population works without being mentioned as employees in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregularities in registration, another reminder of working in the state is low wages; the state has the lowest wages in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Welfare.
Sinaloa workers' monthly average income was 5,352 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reducing FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment in 2011, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July, the state's FDI was $630,697.
The state government's Ministry of Economic Development recorded a total of 17,280,000 pesos of investment over the year, mostly for service companies.
Debt
In the wake of the economic downturn, the state government asked the state congress in July to approve a 3 billion pesos loan that would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved locally, and by November, no debt gains were expected in any sector of the state economy.
The reaction
For business people, the first year of Mario Lopez Valdés's government demonstrates a lack of government capability.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that there was a lack of consensus among various sectors, including the state government itself, during 2011.
"The economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, it takes a lot of work to get back to the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, first of all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Lopez Loredo said events like the early freezes have stalled the state's economy this year and its efficiency and growth have been limited.
"Low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including a frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not getting fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and therefore at the end of the year we close it below our expectations", he said.
Revisiting the direction
Theodore Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue its most dynamic production activity.
"In general, we found that we were working on this, we believe that we need to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, we need to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction to better direct government efforts.
"In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program", he said.
He noted that the current administration has made progress in its own manner of conducting public policy.
