The court will approve the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The shift from analog to digital is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court (Supreme Court) rejected constitutional claims by the Senate and House of Representatives against the presidential decree that moves the so-called "transition to digital television" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to overturn it were not cast.
A minority of the four ministers, including the court's President, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes needed for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional because regulating radio and television programs is a law-enforced right for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to disprove the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said he disagreed with the draft's arguments in the sense that the federal executive cannot define the general rules for measures to be prepared by the state administration.
"I also do not believe that if this happens, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and reminded that planning public policy in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, governance of the state.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that has occurred in recent years, resulting in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transforming into a digital form that includes meeting societal needs that has not only a technical dimension, "as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, including a group of authorities that the Constitution unites into the state executive power".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures that the laws passed by the Legislature are upheld in the administrative sphere, he said.
In Michoacan, they're analyzing the ability to count "voice by voice"
According to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, which are 879 out of a total of 6,074 minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is real for the election process this year in Michoacan, where, according to data from the Preliminary Election Results Program (PPRD), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, which are 879 out of a total of 6,074 minutes.
In light of this, the chairman of the General Council of the Michoacan Institute of Elections (IEC), Maria de Los Angeles Llanderal Saragossa, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral college approved a set of principles to align local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be noted that Michoacan did not adopt the Constitution or the state Electoral Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the state Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal term for their entry into force in this election process and Governor Lionel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the deadlines set by the law in the Official Gazette of the state, stating that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJJ) ruled on a constitutional claim by the local legislature and called the state's constitutional reform representative's voice "untrue and illegal" because he had no right to "allow or support them".
In an interview about the possibility of "voice for voice" Maria de los Angeles Llanderald argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council of the IAM it would be possible for the local electorate to submit a partial or full count of votes.
For example, a partial recount of one or more polling stations may be made on the condition that: the results of the minutes do not match; there is no voting and document counting record in the polling station or it is not with the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, a general count of votes in all polling stations may take place when there is evidence that the difference between the presumed winner of the elections and the second-place candidate in the vote is less than or equal to one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that put forward the second candidate.
The total number of votes will also be counted if at the end of the usual counting it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate who took second place is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate took second place, in the event that the polling stations that were taken into account in the partial counting are excluded.
It is worth noting that elections are in Moralia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting 129 votes out of a total of 923 in the minutes.
