On Wednesday , a new Italian government will be formed .
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to present a new government that will face the crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic catastrophe.
Italy's appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic catastrophe and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to introduce a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive branch will take its position.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his negotiations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles were overcome.
"The structure is well-outlined now", he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought the size of their debt to a critical level
The administration led by former European Commissioner Monty must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Under pressure from Monte to hurry, volatile markets set a 10-year yield on Italy's BTP bonds at more than 7 percent, a level Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegali, leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told reporters after meeting Monty: "We said we would actively support this government".
We believe this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, to reporters.
The support of the LDP, Italy's largest party, is important because until now many of its members have opposed the governmental majority of technocrats that Monty forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspending of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has increased pressure, warning that the failure of Monti could be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He's finishing his meeting on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed by Napolitano on Sunday, who allowed an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief hiatus at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italy's debt value has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy with a 1.8 billion euro debt would be too much for the modern financial backers of the eurozone.
Monti said his government would exist until the next election scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before another election was scheduled.
Monti said he would like politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should be composed of only technical experts, a sign of their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources said that the mutual distrust and disagreement of the parties complicated the attempt to include political figures.
