Quintet included the country in the tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of his career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.
In an exclusive interview with Viva bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to give one of their best shows next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says it's also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
That's what bassist and founder Jeff Ament said, who gave an exclusive interview with Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on tour in South America to celebrate their 20th anniversary and will make their only stop in Central America on Sunday, November 20.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium beginning at 7:30 p.m. with the Los Angeles-based band The X and the local band Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from a conversation that's fully decrypted online at The Nation.
For your fans in Costa Rica, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far, everything is going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once - on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
So we're very happy to bring our music there.
I ask this because there's some loyalty to the band; the fans live in tension the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, treat it like the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've had some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that's got us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle, and in terms of those two things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surf wave?
We have a lot of surfer friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarind, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua and Mexico, which are great places to surf, and that's how we learned about it from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can tell you've done some great shows with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the show in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We're going to try to make the best show possible with the most diverse songs; we're going to try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How's that work?
I think part of it's because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us, because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might forget.
It makes the show more interesting to us, and that's why I think it makes it more interesting to people.
This tour is your 20th career anniversary.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, of course.
First of all, I don't think either of us could ever have imagined that we'd be in a rock band and that doing it for over 20 years makes it a dream.
We're happy with our success and we're very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we love making music.
We're happy to travel to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
We're having a very good time.
What does it mean to you to be a big part of the grass?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We're good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's great when the movement grows out of a group of friends, and that's unusual.
Occasionally, there's one group from the same city, but it's much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle band.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're happy to be friends with them all and we're honored to be part of the Seattle sound that worked.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stay together and in the same lineup for so long.
Yeah, the four of us were together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is a lot longer than most bands do.
First, I think we're lucky to be alive, and second, we care about others.
We're all very close friends, and that's what's also opened up musical pathways that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and it couldn't have been any better.
Your attitude to the word fame was not easy, but thanks to your success, you could do whatever you wanted.
How do you find the balance?
As we grew older, it became easier to find balance.
We're making sure we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to get into this game with a lot of people and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you have to respect music and what made it, not by choosing to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and didn't release an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of disappointment because it went on for so long, and most importantly, we're still close friends with Bruce (Fairwester) and Greg (Gilmore), who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think about the incredible person Andy was, and the way he made me laugh, it was always the pleasure of going to work, laughing, talking about music and football and so much more.
He was a wonderful man, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the producers sent us a couple of videos, and this was the band we liked the most, so we can't wait to see what Las Robertas have to offer live, and it's got to be really exciting.
Why do you always change the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
The first to come to mind are Geiser Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukovsky...
There are so many of them, I can talk all day about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping the grunge alive even though it's out of fashion?
I think we all feel a little bit separated from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all of the other bands that came out around the same time, and if that's important now, I think it's great because it's music that's worth listening to, and teams like Mudhoney are making music better than ever.
At first your music was darker, but now it's more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that might seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, even though they may sound a little positive.
Both of those songs when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, and those songs were very dark.
I think that when you grow up and you've had some trauma in your life and you've lost a family member or a friend, those events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that to me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
