Fuhimori was hospitalized again for medical examination
Former president Alberto Fuchimori was hospitalized Tuesday at a state hospital for a loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fuhimori, 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is under surveillance.
Congressman Alejandro Aginag, who is his personal physician, told TV channel N that Fuchimori would be examined for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aginagami said that he thought Fuhimori should be a candidate for the graces of mercy for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he did not want to do so because he knew he was innocent.
He underwent four operations for tongue cancer, lost 18 pounds, and other ailments, such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and problems with blood circulation in his legs, the doctor said.
Fuhimori has been in prison since September 2007, at the National Police Office of Special Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for killing 25 people by the forces of an army of destruction that operated in secret during his first years in power.
Mujica goes to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and businessmen will arrive in Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and to start negotiations on the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the most important point of a comprehensive plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and meetings with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to a schedule published by the Uruguay leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will be "a favorable opportunity for the exchange of information on the political relations between the two nations", the South American country's leadership said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking support from Calderon for Uruguay in the incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in the list of tax havens at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that sparked protests from Uruguay and a recall for consultations with his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairman of the G20 since November, a group of the most developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax swaps to leave the Organization's "grey list" of countries that do not use international tax cooperation standards.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004, which increased trade between the two countries.
