At a press conference, Kolom said his decision was related to the independence of the judiciary and executive, given that the court of first instance had already signed the extradition.
He claimed that during his tenure he had not "put his hands on" legal decisions and had taken all the extradition procedures he had ever known.
Along with Portillo Sergio Ruano Marroquin will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, as well as Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did shows the executive process after all the legal and constitutional courts were exhausted to prosecute the former head of state from 2000 to 2004.
Pursuant to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited once with a decision on his legal status in Guatemala and guaranteed his human rights.
Portillo was found not guilty of squandering Q120 million at the Ministry of Defence during the presidential term, which was a process leading to his extradition, but the Ministry of Public Affairs appealed and reopened the case.
