During the work, pieces of the aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the ground has a tilt of seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The pictures show the sequence in which it was destroyed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to suggest that the helicopter may have had several crashes.
After careful scrutiny of a larger area than the outlined area near the crash site, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, reinforcing the assumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity.
MSS announces a gene search program for obesity
Social protection leads the research on finding the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) announced that it is conducting a study to detect an obesity gene in children and young people, which is called the Protocol on the Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity, which will provide a count of signs associated with being overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit at the National Medical Center's Specialized Hospital of the XXI Century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multi-profile team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and postdoctoral fellows of the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invites the public (prescribed or not) to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children will be conducted every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol was started at the sports center in Kwautemok (to the west of the state of Mexico), and from October 8 the events are held at the sports center in Nesawalkootla (to the east of the state of Mexico).
Once the goal of involving 500 to 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (south of Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify the risk factor among children and young Mexicans for preventing chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14 and the main goal is to gather 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission and supervision of their parents to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of inherited diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be conducted.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health care professionals' concern about the alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that there was an increase in just 6 years: 77 percent of boys were obese, 47 percent of girls were obese; and there was a significant increase in overweight", said an MSSI specialist.
He said the validity of the marker search is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from other nations in their genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican is 65 percent of American Indian descent, 30 percent of European and five percent of African descent, and this condition was influenced by genes that are linked to diabetes and being overweight.
He explained that the main effect of obesity genetics is the body's inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and then store it as fat.
The researcher explained that a direct benefit to participants is a comprehensive assessment of children that can determine whether they are at least in some degree overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck and forearms means a chance of metabolic impairment and even pre-diabetes.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, and the doctors pass it on in writing to the parents, who they explain to all the measures and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the television, and using transportation for short distances instead of walking.
It's also due to high calorie intake, which is increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tams, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Errera, a researcher at the UNAM School of Chemistry, developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the highest quality, environmentally and temperature resistant.
If the signals sent by the road cover were to be taken into account, about 200,000 pits would need to be repaired each rainy season in the downtown area of Mexico City's Valley, says Rafael Errera Naher, a researcher at UNAM's Chemical Faculty, adding that if the process of building and maintaining the asphalt road cover is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture, Technological Look at the Pit, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Errera Nahera said this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, like in some cities in the north, to improve road quality and thus counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscous behavior.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees, it's very viscous, and at 50 degrees Celsius, it's almost solid, while at very low temperatures, bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperatures, said a chemical engineer.
A chimpanzee noted that Mexico's streets are mostly covered with flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Between the top layers is bitumen, made of small stones that are lowered into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When vehicles are moving and exercising their efforts, this helps the forces to be very well distributed along the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, it would have distributed even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt surface, he added, is the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also submerged in asphalt.
Since this is the layer that will come into contact with the wheels of the vehicle, it should have more resistance than the asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute this effort, the wear layer also requires the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it has a significant impact on the state of the asphalt.
When the soil is raw, water penetrates the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of it, it causes all the layers of the coating to soften and hence the formation of a pit.
When the pits are formed, he said, the wear layer is first worn out and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, a process that should be taken into account at the first sign of current repair programs.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transportation loads are another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be related to transportation loads and this requirement must be guaranteed to be met to prevent frequent occurrence of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still much to be studied and done about bitumen, such as bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help to repair wells with ease and without using high temperatures.
