Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma
If there's a topic that you can't decide after a short discussion or emotionally, it's energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It's a healthy trend that election meetings are an opportunity to reflect on the role and place of nuclear power.
The dispute will not be settled until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are explored.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
We have seven billion people on the planet now, and the demographic development will double our electricity needs by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of vital resources.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing fossil-fuel shortage to continue producing electricity continuously, while not forgetting the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalance, a topic that has disappeared from environmental debate.
The Fukushima disaster doesn't change any of these factors.
That's why Germany is alone in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which has decided to find a source that can replace nuclear power, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are firmly pursuing their projects.
The United States decided to add one installation to its suite after Fukushima, resuming construction of the station, which was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
Although Germany's renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by the increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a surge in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
We should consider the example of Denmark.
It is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to the winds that break; therefore, carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to our consistent energy policy, our neighbors are paying 40% more for electricity than French households.
In a globalized economy, energy prices are a key factor in competitiveness and the maintenance of industrial equipment in the national territory, and French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in electricity prices, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of our purchasing power.
The price most French people refuse to pay, especially because they don't object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole host of small and medium-sized enterprises specialized in international trade and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear power, it would have to donate a large number of these plants and lose 6,000 million euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to last sixty years if the plant was scheduled to close?
To solve the energy equation, we must recognize that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest level of security for nuclear energy is undoubtedly a vital issue
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centers like Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are filled with the same obsession with safety.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has been through three major incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was operated under normal conditions, but without any human or environmental impact.
In Chernobyl, the reactor's design and an unforgivable human error led to a tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented strength that killed tens of thousands.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, just as it did from the two previous ones.
The result of this step and the cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that allows us to counter such phenomena.
As it is being considered by all energy professionals who want to build a reactor, the plant's completion in Flamanville will be a great gift to Areva and EDF competitors, paving the way for them to become leaders in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important to the economic, social and financial well-being of our country.
Is Immigration a Burden or a Good for the Economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized by various parties - overloading police, judicial and administrative services, subservient to the policy of numbers, and the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative oppression of foreign students, which got in the news when the minister of the interior (Libération, May 23) declared that France "did not need foreign talent, stoneworkers and waiters".
But it's rarely analyzed from an economic standpoint.
The right and left are largely in agreement on this issue.
On the right side, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed people will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France "cannot accept the poor from all over the world".
The difference is only in the level of generosity
In 2005, the Polish water-pipeller's horde felt fear of invasion of the country by both the left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity they're willing to show to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limited himself to the trivial, saying that "working together will solve our immigration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but it's very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Foreign People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Shape Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.
Limiting immigration leads to slower growth and lower employment.
The fear of immigrant influence is based on the idea that they can replace local workers, especially low-skilled workers, causing a decline in wages.
But experience shows that immigrants actually supplement local labor force far more than they replace it with jobs that lack local labor force.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour, while the most skilled work in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants has led to the influx of immigrants having a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Perry estimated that a 1% increase in the migration flow would lead to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And that's without considering the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring in contributes to new ideas and economic growth (among the Nobel Prize winners in America, the number of naturalized immigrants is high, and Google, Intel, Paypal, and Yahoo - all of them were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net income to the social security system, contributing on average 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates that, for example, an immigrant arriving in Germany at the age of 30, will bring a net profit (income minus expenses) of an average of 150,000 euros to the state budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his term, was going to "tooth" to cling to the missing growth points.
The teeth that were used to scare off immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to be understood European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition; but it is also fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some believed that for democracy to finally conquer its enemies, it was enough to arrange a vote and make it as straightforward as possible.
It's been known since the time of Napoleon the Younger that this is the surface of thought.
General voting, although a mandatory condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of repression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Washro once said.
No, democracy requires much more - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation of powers and control, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but first of all it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have a double-disclosure effect, demonstrating both the need for a major policy change and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood to be overcome.
The truth is that the front line of the fight for democracy has now shifted and many believe that Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We won't win anything by demanding a series of national referendums organized as necessary and in a chaotic order.
A card-blush for an absolute European monarch or a leg-bound leap into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we are not dreaming of a guillotine blade, but of a common, clear and continuous choice and democracy, this time at a European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it's not clear how many more will have to be listed, because there's only one crisis - the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but all of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The management of the European project must be restored to the sovereignty of the people.
Because only by working together can Europeans reduce the burden of debt, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
The crisis will require solutions at a European level, and they cannot be adopted without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After much discussion of this proposal, the socialists and Jack DeLore are now demanding a European economic government.
Let it be.
But to imagine it without a stronger economic, political and democratic integration, which has been brought into existence by citizens, is another madness and a new deadlock.
We must begin a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, you had to "create" the Republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
This lesson remains in effect.
We must build a Europe that is economically united.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European sovereignty of the people.
To create Europe, let's create Europeans.
