The North Stream, new gateway for Russian gas to Europe.
The North Stream gas pipeline connecting Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea has been launched.
It's designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households with gas.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the orchestra's performance and the fine snacks, in the opening of the Northern Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rütte have all rolled the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline will supply 27,5 million cubic meters of gas each year to Western Europe via the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomeranian.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 thousand million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France's consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, completing this huge project on time is a victory.
The project was met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
The North Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at the alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
That means the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a rift between Eastern and Western Europe.
Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of the direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
"This gas pipeline is part of our cooperation with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically", said François Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the importance of large gas contracts both politically and economically.
All this explains the large smiles on the faces of Gazprom's heads who were present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel, sealed in concrete to protect it from anchorage.
It's on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, you had to bypass the minefields left over from World War II.
"The water was removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Mueller, a spokesman for North Stream.
Many steps were also needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metallic snake weighing the equivalent of 242 Eiffel Towers, with no gaps along its entire length, no valves and no service stations.
A control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers refused it because Sweden was not happy that a Russian state-owned company would settle permanently on its shores.
"In the event of an accident, we'll shut down the gas in less than a minute", says Jens Mueller.
So, in the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will go into the air.
But that seems unlikely to the designers who designed seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
The control of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-shaped device is inserted into a 1 meter diameter pipeline and pushed forward by the gas stream.
When he arrives after three full days of traveling at a speed of three meters per second, he gives accurate information about any metal deformation.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any repairs.
The gas circulates only at its pressure.
It's 200 bars on departure and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called North Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for 20 years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
"Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Mueller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez's investment will be about $240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident they'll pay their bills because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The pipeline runs from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
The 4.5 meter high vents form the exhaust gas terminal.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it'll be 3 million an hour, and in 2012, it'll be 6 million.
