Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Week 15 of disability employment begins today.
Despite the public charity policy that began in 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is still twice the average, at 19% versus 9% for the general population.
Discouraging?
"No", says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of disability employment.
"In 15 years, we've made a lot of progress".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two times higher, but three times higher".
"But there's still a lot of work to do".
I must say that there are many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them there are more elderly: 37% over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a rather low level of qualifications: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for disabled people versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the core of the problem", says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There's no need to talk about a mentality that changes, but too slowly.
A study commissioned by the IMS-Entreprendre association in April by Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "imagined themselves as solid people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally incomplete".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of having 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 law.
The latest known figures, dated 2008, give a value of 2.6%.
"Today we're about 3 percent", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization that collects taxes on companies that don't comply with the law.
Evidence: the number of "taxable" organisations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59 000 to 46 000 organisations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 tax law put a lot of pressure on the company", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects the increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises".
According to the employment ministry, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees, compared with 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
